Titer Response Analysis

Marco Kreuzer

IBU
marco.kreuzer@unibe.ch

19.05.2025

Background

When evaluating vaccine-induced immune responses, a common approach is to compute the fold change in antibody titers from baseline to outcome. However, fold changes are biased by baseline titers — individuals with high baseline titers typically show lower relative increases (and vice versa). This confounding effect complicates comparisons between individuals.

To correct for this, the following strategies were used:

  1. Classification based on linear model with max response titer.

  2. Classification based on linear model with sum response titer (the corrected fold change was summed up across all strains)

  3. A dense ranking approach of the summed titers

  4. . Method 1 (Beyer et al.): Adjust the outcome titers via linear regression to a common baseline, then compute fold changes.

Data Transformation

df <- read.csv("titer_data.csv")

# Pivot longer to isolate strain + metric info
df_long <- df %>%
  pivot_longer(
    cols = starts_with("hai_") | starts_with("microneut_"),
    names_to = "key",
    values_to = "value"
  ) %>%
  mutate(
    measurement = case_when(
      str_starts(key, "hai_") ~ "hai",
      str_starts(key, "microneut_") ~ "microneut"
    ),
    strain = str_extract(key, "(H1N1|H3N2|BVic|BYam)"),
    metric = case_when(
      str_detect(key, "ic50") ~ "ic50",
      TRUE ~ "titer"
    )
  ) %>%
  select(Pat_ID, pat_group, Titer_type, strain, measurement, metric, value)

# Pivot wider based on Titer_type (baseline/outcome). 
df_wide <- df_long %>%
  pivot_wider(
    names_from = Titer_type,
    values_from = value
  ) %>%
  rename(
    baseline = baseline_titer,
    outcome = outcome_titer
  )

# Calculate fold change and standardize. Note that standardisation is done within measurement, strain and metric
df_fc <- df_wide %>%
  mutate(
    fold_change = outcome / baseline
  ) %>%
  group_by(measurement, strain, metric) %>%
  mutate(
    fc_std_norm = (fold_change - median(fold_change, na.rm = TRUE)) / sd(fold_change, na.rm = TRUE),
    baseline_std_norm = (baseline - median(baseline, na.rm = TRUE)) / sd(baseline, na.rm = TRUE)
  ) %>%
  ungroup()

Classification based on linear model with max response titer

To identify vaccine responders, we used a standardized fold change approach based on each individual’s strongest antibody response.

  1. Standardization
    Fold changes (outcome / baseline titer) were computed for each patient and influenza strain. These values were then standardized (z-scored) across all patients and strains to enable comparison across the cohort.

  2. Maximal Response Selection
    For each patient, we selected the strain with the highest standardized fold change which represents the most pronounced response. The corresponding baseline titer for that strain was paired as a predictor.

  3. Linear Model Adjustment
    A linear regression model was fitted: Standardized Fold Change_max ~ Standardized Baseline Titer

The residuals from this model (referred to as padjMFC) represent how much stronger or weaker a patient’s response was compared to others with similar baseline titers.

  1. Responder Classification

Patients were classified based on either 20 or 30 % quantiles.

  • High responders: Top 20 or top 30% of patients

  • Moderate responders: Middle range

  • Low responders: Bottom 20 or bottom 30% of patients

This approach adjusts for baseline immunity and highlights individuals with unusually strong or weak vaccine responses.

df_responder <- df_fc %>%
  filter(measurement == "hai", metric == "titer") %>%
  group_by(Pat_ID) %>%
  mutate(
    fc_norm_max_ivt = max(fc_std_norm, na.rm = TRUE),
    d0_norm_paired = baseline_std_norm[which.max(fc_std_norm)]
  ) %>%
  slice_max(fc_std_norm, n = 1, with_ties = FALSE) %>%
  ungroup()

model <- lm(fc_norm_max_ivt ~ d0_norm_paired, data = df_responder)

df_responder <- df_responder %>%
  mutate(padjMFC = augment(model, data = .)$`.resid`)

discretize <- c(0.2, 0.3)
responseLabels <- c("lowResponder", "moderateResponder", "highResponder")

for (dis in discretize) {
  q_low <- quantile(df_responder$padjMFC, dis, na.rm = TRUE)
  q_high <- quantile(df_responder$padjMFC, 1 - dis, na.rm = TRUE)

  df_responder <- df_responder %>%
    mutate(!!paste0("padjMFC_d", dis * 100) := factor(case_when(
      is.na(padjMFC) ~ NA_character_,
      padjMFC <= q_low ~ responseLabels[1],
      padjMFC >= q_high ~ responseLabels[3],
      TRUE ~ responseLabels[2]
    ), levels = responseLabels))
}

Classification Based on Linear Model with Sums of the Response Titers

To capture the overall vaccine response across all HAI strains per individual, we implemented a sum-based approach. This method provides a comprehensive view by integrating fold change responses across strains rather than focusing on a single maximum value.

Methodology

  • Summation of Fold Changes
    For each patient, standardized fold changes (fc_std_norm) were summed across all HAI strains. Similarly, the standardized baseline titers were also summed. This produced a patient-level summary of total vaccine-induced responsiveness and pre-existing immunity.

  • Linear Model Adjustment
    A linear model was fitted to adjust for the confounding effect of cumulative baseline titers:

    \[ \text{Sum of Standardized Fold Changes} \sim \text{Sum of Standardized Baseline Titers} \]

    The model residuals (padjMFC) quantify how much stronger or weaker a patient’s overall response was compared to what would be expected given their baseline immunity.

  • Responder Classification
    As in the previous section, patients were classified using quantiles of the residual distribution:

    • High responders: Top 20% / 30% of adjusted residuals
    • Low responders: Bottom 20% / 30%
    • Moderate responders: Remaining individuals

    This quantile-based classification helps highlight individuals with unusually strong or weak global responses, while accounting for baseline variation.

df_responder_sum <- df_fc %>%
  filter(measurement == "hai", metric == "titer") %>%
  group_by(Pat_ID) %>%
  summarise(
    pat_group = first(pat_group),
    fc_norm_sum_ivt = sum(fc_std_norm, na.rm = TRUE),
    d0_norm_sum = sum(baseline_std_norm, na.rm = TRUE),
    .groups = "drop"
  )

model_sum <- lm(fc_norm_sum_ivt ~ d0_norm_sum, data = df_responder_sum)

df_responder_sum <- df_responder_sum %>%
  mutate(padjMFC = augment(model_sum, data = .)$`.resid`)

discretize <- c(0.2, 0.3)
responseLabels <- c("lowResponder", "moderateResponder", "highResponder")

for (dis in discretize) {
  q_low <- quantile(df_responder_sum$padjMFC, dis, na.rm = TRUE)
  q_high <- quantile(df_responder_sum$padjMFC, 1 - dis, na.rm = TRUE)

  df_responder_sum <- df_responder_sum %>%
    mutate(!!paste0("padjMFC_d", dis * 100) := factor(case_when(
      is.na(padjMFC) ~ NA_character_,
      padjMFC <= q_low ~ responseLabels[1],
      padjMFC >= q_high ~ responseLabels[3],
      TRUE ~ responseLabels[2]
    ), levels = responseLabels))
}

Summarizing Both Methods

To evaluate the agreement between the two classification strategies — one based on the maximum response titer and the other on the sum of responses across strains — we compared the assigned responder classes (lowResponder, moderateResponder, highResponder) for each individual.

Comparison Strategy

  • Responder labels (lowResponder, moderateResponder, highResponder) were obtained for each patient using both methods at 20% and 30% quantile cutoffs.
  • A contingency matrix was created to count how many individuals were assigned to each combination of responder classes across the two methods.
  • Heatmaps were generated to visualize the overlap and discrepancies in classification.

Interpretation

The resulting heatmaps show how consistently patients are categorized by both approaches:

  • Diagonal dominance (i.e., high counts along the diagonal) indicates strong agreement between methods.
  • Off-diagonal values reflect discrepancies, highlighting individuals who were classified differently depending on whether the max or the sum of responses was used.
  • Comparing the 20% and 30% quantile thresholds helps evaluate the robustness of classification boundaries.
df_compare <- df_responder %>%
  select(Pat_ID, max_d20 = padjMFC_d20, max_d30 = padjMFC_d30) %>%
  left_join(df_responder_sum %>%
              select(Pat_ID, sum_d20 = padjMFC_d20, sum_d30 = padjMFC_d30),
            by = "Pat_ID")

df_heatmap <- df_compare %>%
  pivot_longer(cols = c(max_d20, sum_d20, max_d30, sum_d30),
               names_to = c("method", "quantile"),
               names_pattern = "(max|sum)_d(\\d+)",
               values_to = "responder_class") %>%
  pivot_wider(names_from = method, values_from = responder_class) %>%
  count(quantile, max, sum) 

ggplot(df_heatmap, aes(x = max, y = sum, fill = n)) +
  geom_tile(color = "white") +
  geom_text(aes(label = n), color = "black", size = 5) +
  scale_fill_gradient(low = "white", high = "steelblue") +
  facet_wrap(~ quantile, labeller = label_both) +
  labs(
    title = "Agreement between Max- and Sum-based Responder Classifications",
    x = "Max-based Classification",
    y = "Sum-based Classification",
    fill = "Count"
  ) +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(
    axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90)
  )

Dense Ranking Method

As an alternative to regression-based approaches, we implemented a dense ranking strategy to classify influenza vaccine responders. This method does not rely on parametric modeling and instead evaluates patients based on their relative position within strain-specific response distributions.

Methodology

  • Step 1: Residual Calculation per Strain
    For each strain, a linear regression model was fit:

    \[ \text{Fold Change} \sim \text{Baseline Titer} \]

    The residuals from these models represent the degree of response after adjusting for baseline levels — a higher residual indicates a better-than-expected response.

  • Step 2: Dense Ranking within Strain
    Within each strain, individuals were ranked by descending residuals, assigning the same rank to ties. This generates a fair comparison within each strain.

  • Step 3: Summation Across Strains
    Residual ranks were summed across all strains for each patient to compute a total rank score. Patients were then ranked again based on their cumulative performance across all strains.

  • Step 4: Classification by Final Rank
    Based on the final ranks, patients were classified into responder categories using 20% and 30% quantile thresholds:

    • High responders: Lowest total ranks (top 20% or 30%)
    • Low responders: Highest total ranks (bottom 20% or 30%)
    • Moderate responders: Middle quantiles

Considerations

This method avoids assumptions about the distribution of fold changes and focuses purely on relative performance across the cohort. However, it may be sensitive to noise in individual strain responses and does not explicitly correct for baseline confounding beyond linear residual adjustment.

It offers a non-parametric complement to the previous regression-based methods and may be useful when response distributions are skewed or non-Gaussian.

# 1. Fit residuals per strain (you’ve done this before)
resid_df <- df_fc %>%
  filter(measurement == "hai", metric == "titer") %>%
  group_by(strain) %>%
  nest() %>%
  mutate(
    model = purrr::map(data, ~ lm(fold_change ~ baseline, data = .x)),
    augmented = purrr::map2(model, data, ~ broom::augment(.x, data = .y))
  ) %>%
  unnest(augmented) %>%
  select(Pat_ID, strain, .resid)



# 2. Rank residuals (higher residual = better response)
rank_residuals <- resid_df %>%
  group_by(strain) %>%
  mutate(rank_resid = dense_rank(desc(.resid))) %>%
  ungroup()

# 3. Sum ranks and get final responder rank
df_rank_summary <- rank_residuals %>%
  group_by(Pat_ID) %>%
  summarise(
    total_rank_score = sum(rank_resid, na.rm = TRUE),
    .groups = "drop"
  ) %>%
  mutate(
    final_rank = dense_rank(total_rank_score)
  )


discretize <- c(0.2, 0.3)
responseLabels <- c("lowResponder", "moderateResponder", "highResponder")

df_rank_summary <- df_rank_summary %>%
  mutate(
    padjRank_d20 = case_when(
      final_rank <= quantile(final_rank, 0.2, na.rm = TRUE) ~ "highResponder",
      final_rank >= quantile(final_rank, 0.8, na.rm = TRUE) ~ "lowResponder",
      TRUE ~ "moderateResponder"
    ),
    padjRank_d30 = case_when(
      final_rank <= quantile(final_rank, 0.3, na.rm = TRUE) ~ "highResponder",
      final_rank >= quantile(final_rank, 0.7, na.rm = TRUE) ~ "lowResponder",
      TRUE ~ "moderateResponder"
    )
  )

Beyer-style Correction

Beyer et al. proposed a correction strategy to adjust for the confounding effects of high baseline titers when evaluating influenza vaccine responses. Their method involves working in log2-transformed space to linearize titer values and mitigate scale distortions.

Methodology

  • Step 1: Log2 Transformation
    Both baseline and outcome titers are transformed using the binary logarithm (log2). This transformation stabilizes variance and simplifies multiplicative relationships into additive ones.

  • Step 2: Raw Log2 Fold Change
    A fold change is calculated in the log2-transformed space, defined as:

    \[ \text{log2\_fc} = \frac{\log_2(\text{outcome})}{\log_2(\text{baseline})} \]

    Note: This formulation has interpretability issues, so it’s primarily diagnostic at this step.

  • Step 3: Linear Model Correction
    A linear model is fitted:

    \[ \log_2(\text{outcome}) \sim \log_2(\text{baseline}) \]

    The slope of this model captures how outcome titers scale with baseline titers. The predicted effect of the baseline is then subtracted to yield a corrected log2 outcome titer:

    \[ \log_2(\text{outcome\_corrected}) = \log_2(\text{outcome}) - b \cdot \log_2(\text{baseline}) \]

  • Step 4: Summarization and Classification
    Corrected log2 outcome titers are summed across all strains for each patient. Based on the distribution, patients are classified into:

    • High responders: Top 20% / 30%
    • Low responders: Bottom 20% / 30%
    • Moderate responders: Middle range

This approach enables fair comparison of vaccine-induced responses while controlling for baseline immunity.

# transform titers to binary logarithm.

df_fc <- df_fc %>% 
    mutate(
    log2_baseline = log2(baseline),
    log2_outcome = log2(outcome)
  )
df_fc %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x=log2_baseline, y=log2_outcome)) +
  geom_point() +
  facet_wrap(~strain)

df_fc <- df_fc %>% 
    mutate(
    log2_fc = log2_outcome / log2_baseline  )
df_fc %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x=log2_baseline, y=log2_fc)) +
  geom_point() +
  facet_wrap(~strain)

Now we fit alinear model and recalculate the fold-change

model <- lm(log2_outcome ~ log2_baseline, data = df_fc)

# Extract slope (b)
b <- coef(model)["log2_baseline"]

# Calculate corrected post-vaccination log2 titer
df_fc <- df_fc %>%
  mutate(
    log2_outcome_corrected = log2_outcome - b * log2_baseline
  )

Now we can redo the plot to see if the distribution is better:

df_fc %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x=log2_baseline, y=log2_outcome_corrected)) +
  geom_point() +
  facet_wrap(~strain)

This makes sense, we don’t have the skewed distriution anymore. Therefore, we can now compare the outcome titers directly.

However, we need to sum them up first:

df_beyer <- df_fc %>% 
  group_by(Pat_ID) %>% 
  summarise(log2_outcome_corrected = sum(log2_outcome_corrected))

Responder Classification Based on Corrected Outcome Titers

discretize <- c(0.2, 0.3)
responseLabels <- c("lowResponder", "moderateResponder", "highResponder")


for (dis in discretize) {
  q_low <- quantile(df_beyer$log2_outcome_corrected, dis, na.rm = TRUE)
  q_high <- quantile(df_beyer$log2_outcome_corrected, 1 - dis, na.rm = TRUE)

  df_beyer <- df_beyer %>%
    mutate(!!paste0("padjBeyer_d", dis * 100) := factor(case_when(
      is.na(log2_outcome_corrected) ~ NA_character_,
      log2_outcome_corrected <= q_low ~ responseLabels[1],
      log2_outcome_corrected >= q_high ~ responseLabels[3],
      TRUE ~ responseLabels[2]
    ), levels = responseLabels))
}

Summary

To compare the classification results across all four methods, we consolidated the responder labels into a unified matrix for visualization. Each method was applied at two quantile thresholds: 20% and 30%, resulting in eight distinct classification outputs per patient.

Method Overview

The following methods were included in the comparison:

  • Max-based regression residuals (padjMax)
  • Sum-based regression residuals (padjSum)
  • Dense rank-based method (padjRank)
  • Beyer-style correction with summed log2 outcomes (padjBeyer)

Approach

  1. All responder classifications (lowResponder, moderateResponder, highResponder) were recoded numerically:
    • 0 = lowResponder
    • 1 = moderateResponder
    • 2 = highResponder
  2. A heatmap matrix was constructed where:
    • Rows represent each method at a given quantile (e.g., Max_20, Sum_30)
    • Columns represent individual patients
    • Cell colors represent responder class
  3. The heatmaps were split by quantile threshold (20% and 30%) and clustered to reveal patterns of agreement and disagreement.
df_combined <- df_responder %>%
  select(Pat_ID, padjMax_d20 = padjMFC_d20, padjMax_d30 = padjMFC_d30) %>%
  left_join(df_responder_sum %>% select(Pat_ID, padjSum_d20 = padjMFC_d20, padjSum_d30 = padjMFC_d30), by = "Pat_ID") %>%
  left_join(df_rank_summary %>% select(Pat_ID, padjRank_d20, padjRank_d30), by = "Pat_ID") %>% 
  left_join(df_beyer %>% select(Pat_ID, padjBeyer_d20, padjBeyer_d30 ))
## Joining with `by = join_by(Pat_ID)`
df_long_heatmap <- df_combined %>%
  pivot_longer(
    cols = starts_with("padj"),
    names_to = c("method", "quantile"),
    names_pattern = "padj(.*)_d(\\d+)",
    values_to = "response"
  ) 

df_long_heatmap <- df_long_heatmap %>%
  mutate(
    method_quant = paste0(method, "_", quantile),
    response_num = recode(response,
      "lowResponder" = 0,
      "moderateResponder" = 1,
      "highResponder" = 2
    )
  )

Cross-Method Responder Agreement

To assess the consistency of patient classification across all four methods, we performed a comprehensive agreement analysis.

Methodology

  1. Each patient had up to four labels (one from each method) at two quantile thresholds (20% and 30%).
  2. We defined two levels of agreement:
    • Full agreement: All four methods assign the same responder label (highResponder or lowResponder)
    • Partial agreement: At least three out of four methods agree on the same label
  3. Patients with consistent classifications were identified and summarized by group.

Agreement Summary

summarize_agreement_full_and_partial <- function(df, suffix) {
  # Select relevant columns
  df_sel <- df %>%
    select(Pat_ID, ends_with(suffix)) %>%
    select(-Pat_ID)

  # Count agreement and label
  agreement_info <- df_sel %>%
    apply(1, function(x) {
      tab <- table(x)
      max_agree <- max(tab)
      label <- names(tab)[which.max(tab)]
      return(c(max_agree = max_agree, consensus_label = label))
    }) %>%
    t() %>%
    as.data.frame() %>%
    mutate(
      max_agree = as.integer(max_agree),
      consensus_label = as.character(consensus_label)
    )

  # Filter to relevant responder types
  agreement_info <- agreement_info %>%
    filter(consensus_label %in% c("lowResponder", "highResponder"))

  # Count full (4/4) agreement
  full_agreement <- agreement_info %>%
    filter(max_agree == 4) %>%
    count(agreement_type = "all methods agree", 
          quantile = suffix, 
          consensus_label, 
          name = "n")

  # Count partial (≥3/4) agreement
  partial_agreement <- agreement_info %>%
    filter(max_agree >= 3) %>%
    count(agreement_type = "three or more methods agree", 
          quantile = suffix, 
          consensus_label, 
          name = "n")

  bind_rows(full_agreement, partial_agreement)
}

# Apply to both quantiles
summary_d20 <- summarize_agreement_full_and_partial(df_combined, "d20")
summary_d30 <- summarize_agreement_full_and_partial(df_combined, "d30")

# Combine
final_summary <- bind_rows(summary_d20, summary_d30)

# Output nicely sorted
final_summary <- final_summary %>%
  arrange(quantile, agreement_type, consensus_label)

kableExtra::kable(final_summary) %>%

Group-specific Agreement Table

To understand if consistent responder patterns were group-dependent, we merged patient metadata and generated stratified summaries by pat_group.

pat_metadata <- df_fc %>% 
  select(Pat_ID, pat_group) %>% 
  distinct()

df_combined <- df_combined %>% 
  left_join(pat_metadata)
## Joining with `by = join_by(Pat_ID)`
df_summary <- df_combined %>% 
  pivot_longer(
    -c("Pat_ID", "pat_group"), names_to = "analysis", values_to = "outcome"
  ) %>% 
  separate(analysis, into = c("analysis", "quantile"), sep = "_")


df_summary <- df_summary %>%
  group_by(Pat_ID, outcome, quantile, pat_group) %>%
  summarise(count = n(), .groups = "drop") %>%
  tidyr::pivot_wider(
    names_from = outcome,
    values_from = count,
    values_fill = 0
  ) %>% 
  mutate(all_high = case_when(
             highResponder == 4 ~ TRUE,
             .default = FALSE),
         gt_three_high = case_when(
           highResponder >= 3 ~ TRUE,
           .default = FALSE
         ),
         all_low = case_when(
           lowResponder == 4 ~ TRUE,
           .default = FALSE
         ),
         gt_three_low = case_when(
           lowResponder >= 3 ~ TRUE,
           .default = FALSE
         ))

Conclusion

We have decided to go for the approach to include all samples where three or more analyses have agreed. We will take the quantile 30 as a start.
